In [[lattice theory]], a mathematical discipline, a finite [[lattice (order)|lattice]] is '''slim''' if no three join-irreducible elements form an [[antichain]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Czédli|Schmidt|2012}}</ref> Every slim lattice is [[planar lattice|planar]]. A finite planar [[semimodular lattice]] is slim if and only if it contains no cover-preserving diamond sublattice M<sub>3</sub> (this is the original definition of a slim lattice due to [[George Grätzer]] and Edward Knapp).<ref>{{harvtxt|Grätzer|Knapp|2007}}</ref>

